  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of some of the key ones:\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988):** This convention, often referred to as the Vienna Convention, was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering. It requires signatory countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations and prosecutions.\n\n*   **The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000):** Also known as the Palermo Convention, this treaty expanded the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include proceeds from a wider range of serious crimes. It also promotes international cooperation in combating organized crime, including money laundering.\n\n*   **The International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** This convention requires states to criminalize the financing of terrorism and to take measures to prevent and counter it. Because money laundering techniques can be used to finance terrorism, this convention has implications for anti-money laundering efforts.\n\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations:** While not a treaty or law in itself, the FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. These standards, known as the FATF Recommendations, are widely recognized and implemented by countries around the world. FATF also monitors countries' compliance with these standards and identifies jurisdictions with weak anti-money laundering regimes.\n\n*   **Regional Agreements:** In addition to these global conventions, there are also regional agreements and initiatives to combat money laundering. For example, the European Union has adopted several directives on anti-money laundering that apply to its member states.\n\nIt's important to note that these international laws and standards provide a framework for national laws and regulations. Countries are responsible for implementing these international obligations into their own legal systems and for enforcing them.",
